Career Choices for your Temperament
Your Temperament
"Success is not the key to happiness. Happiness is the key to success.
If you love what you are doing, you will be successful." - Albert
Schweitzer
Temperament is like the blueprint of who we are from the moment we're born. It shapes
how we react to things and what we're naturally drawn to. Think of it as the foundation of
your personality, influenced by both your genes and early experiences. But as we go
through life, things like how we're raised, the culture we're part of, and the people we're
around, all play a part in shaping and refining our temperament. Even though it changes
over time, those core traits stick with us, guiding how we see the world and how we handle
different situations. Understanding our temperament helps us understand ourselves
better and grow as individuals.
You present a tough persona while your temperament is
caring and a gentle approach to humanity. This temperament
suits careers that require high energy but also a humane
approach and imagination. You may try jobs that are closer
to your home town, so that it allows you to serve humanity
with being close to the family would be highly satisfying for
you.

Notes
Motivation of work
Different people are motivated by different things. Some want to be liked and
accepted by others, so they work hard to fit in and be recognized. Others value
their independence and creativity, preferring to do things their own way and
express themselves freely. Then there are those who strive for excellence in
what they do, aiming to make a positive impact and be the best they can be.
Finally, some are driven by the desire for power and wealth, wanting to achieve
success and control their own destiny. Figuring out what motivates you can
help you set goals and find satisfaction in your work and life.

Notes
Your Strengths (SWOT analysis)
Careers transcend mere jobs, encompassing behavioural, cognitive, people, and
leadership skills alongside employability traits. Aligning with industry demands
ensures success and fulfilment in chosen paths.
When selecting a career, consider four vital aspects:
1. Behavioural Skills: Handle stress, foster creativity,
embrace learning, uphold ethics, and stay resilient.
2. Cognitive Abilities: Analyse situations, reason logically,
grasp complexity, innovate solutions, and communicate
effectively.
3. People and Leadership Skills: Cultivate confidence,
negotiate skilfully, resolve conflicts, lead teams, embrace
diversity, make wise decisions, and inspire others.
4. Employability Skills: Recognize that employability extends
beyond technical skills, encompassing adaptability and
continuous learning.
Assess yourself across these dimensions to align with
industry demands and maximize your potential for success
and fulfilment.
